Unfortunately, this evinces that although the user was not in the situation
 when the data was retrieved, the user is now in a state similar to a dirty
 read, because the data he is using is no longer valid.
 Even after stale data has been noticed by the tacted persistence mechanism,
 Untis does not force an actualization of the data displayed to the user.
 In order for the user to have fresh data displayed he must either refresh
 the window manually by pressing F5 or by closing and reopening the resource
 dialogue.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A similar, but further reaching, concurrency issue is that of external resource
 reservation.
 The booking of external resources, blocks this resource across all schools
 which use this resource, and shows the blocking agent in the planning dialogues.
 This is unfortunately not always the case.
 There have been instances where planned reservations in one school were
 not shown to other schools for some amount of time.
 As this the implementation is not directly documented as the above issue
 it is hard to construct test cases to force the actualization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second concurrency issue addressed by Untis is the restriction of key
 resources.
 Key resources are those which have consequences for the structure of the
 Untis resource school such as the management of school data and planning
 periods.
 Should a person with the appropriate access currently be working with one
 of these protected resources login attempts my other users to this school
 will be denied.
 Should other users already be logged on while attempting to access these
 areas, the user attempting access will either be denied access to the dialogue
 in the case of planning periods, or be reduced to read priveleges in the
 dialogue in the case of school data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Untis in the THM System Landscape
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When Untis was originally being purchased the driving force behind the purchase
 was the database behind it which was the part of a broader concept for
 real time applications which would then use this data for the display of
 schedule information and anything else which Untis through it's internal
 calculations could provide.
 However during the Untis training it was strongly recommended that no applicati
ons be directly based upon the Untis database as its structure and consistency
 could and would not be guarenteed.
 Instead it was recommended that Untis XML export functionality be used
 to export the required data, as its format would be guarenteed.
 This relegated Untis from the strong central position initially envisioned
 to the position of a data source solely for the THM Organizer component.
\end_layout

