\begin_layout Minisec
Preemptive Restriction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although Joomla! through its ACL does offer preemptive restriction THM Organizer
 does not yet make use of this feature.
 In Joomla! this removes menu entries for which the user does not have the
 appropriate rights.
 However, because Joomla! is a web based content management system this
 would only remove the display of URLs which would access such menu items,
 it would not be able to block the direct entry of these URLs into a web
 browser.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Minisec
Postemptive Restriction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a logical consequence of the limits of preemptive restriction, all Joomla!
 software must make use of post emptive restriction.
 Within components, this restriction must be implemented at the two levels
 which can be directly accessed via URLs.
 The first level is within the component's views, these display information
 and can offer actions to the user.
 The second level is the components controllers, these recieve form data
 from user interaction.
 These are the more dangerous of the two as these most often call functions
 of the models which could then modify or destroy data.
\end_layout

